      <div class="section-number">03</div>
      <div class="brand-context-content">
        <h2>The Samsung Ice Maker and Southern California's Coast</h2>
        <p>Here's what actually happens in a coastal Samsung refrigerator ice maker, and why it gets worse the closer you are to the Pacific.</p>
        <p>Samsung French door and 4-Door Flex models have a design characteristic: the ice maker draws air through the dispenser chute opening into the ice maker cavity. In a dry inland environment, this isn't a problem — the air is low-humidity and the evaporator coil inside the cavity stays frost-free between defrost cycles. On the coast, that changes.</p>
        <p>Marine air from the Pacific carries significantly more moisture than inland air. When that humid air is drawn into the ice maker cavity and contacts the cold evaporator coil, moisture condenses and freezes. It builds up gradually — first a thin layer, then thicker accumulation, then eventually the entire mechanism is encased in ice. The ice maker tries to cycle, fails because the mechanism can't move, and stops producing.</p>
        <p>The symptom progression is predictable: ice production slows over a few months, cubes become hollow or smaller than normal, then production stops entirely. By the time production stops, the cavity has usually been accumulating ice for 6-18 months.</p>
        <p>We defrost the cavity, replace the ice maker module (which is typically damaged by the prolonged ice accumulation), and install a duct cover kit — an OEM Samsung part that partially blocks the air pathway into the ice maker, significantly slowing humidity ingress. For properties in Balboa Peninsula, Malibu Colony, Cotton's Point, or other high-exposure coastal locations, we recommend an annual inspection regardless of symptoms.</p>

        <h2>New Construction in SoCal — Wire Harness Failure in Samsung French Doors</h2>
        <p>Since about 2022, we've been seeing a specific failure in Samsung French door refrigerators installed in SoCal's newer construction — Tustin Legacy, the Irvine Spectrum area, new Ventura County developments. These homes got Samsung 4-Door Flex units in 2018-2020. They're now in the 5-7 year failure window.</p>
        <p>The wire harness that runs to the ice maker passes through the left door hinge area. On French door models, this hinge is exercised hundreds of times a year. The harness routing on Samsung's RF28 and RF29 series puts the wire in contact with the hinge bracket under certain door positions. Over years, the insulation chafes through and the wire shorts intermittently — causing the ice maker to fail unpredictably, sometimes after specific temperatures, sometimes randomly.</p>
        <p>The fix is rerouting the harness with a protective sleeve and securing it away from the hinge bracket. This is a relatively simple repair once you know what to look for — but it requires recognizing the pattern. Homeowners get misdiagnosed with ice maker module failures, replaced modules that fail again for the same reason, and sometimes quotes for control boards that had nothing to do with it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

